
[1]sex

   SEX, n. [L. sexus; from L. seco, to divide.]

   1. The distinction between male and female; or the property or
   character by which an animal is male or female. The male sex is usually
   characterized by muscular strength, boldness and firmness. The female
   sex is characterized by softness, sensibility and modesty.

   In botany, the property of plants which corresponds to sex in animals.
   The Linnean system of botany is formed on the doctrine of sexes in
   plants.

   2. By way of emphasis, womankind; females.

   Unhappy sex! whose beauty is your snare. Dryden.
